Office of National Drug Control Policy
Skip to content Open Menu White House Logo Copy URL to your clipboard Share Economy National Security Budget Immigration Coronavirus.gov Search WhiteHouse.gov Open Search Office of National Drug Control Policy The Office of National Drug Control Policy (ONDCP) is a component of the Executive Office of the President which works to reduce drug use and its consequences by leading and coordinating the development, implementation, and assessment of U.S. drug policy. In addition to its vital ongoing work, ONDCP also provided administrative and financial support to the President’s Commission on Combating Drug Addiction and the Opioid Crisis, established by Executive Order on March 29, 2017 by President Donald J. Trump. Share: Share this page on Facebook Share this page on Twitter Copy URL to your clipboard In this section HomeThe AdministrationExecutive OfficesOffice of National Drug Control Policy The Administration’s Approach The Drug Crisis The Administration’s Strategy President’s Commission on Opioids The HIDTA Program Overview Designation Process Program Impacts The DFC Program Overview Application Process Program Impacts Enhancement Grants Other Grant Programs Anti-Doping and Clean Sport Drug Courts Training Model Acts About Authorizations Budget, Performance, and Data Advisories FOIA and Legal Contact Us Established in 1988, ONDCP coordinates the federal government’s anti-drug efforts by: Developing a comprehensive National Drug Control Strategy which aims to reduce substance use through public health and public safety measures; Funding and coordinating the activities of law enforcement, community-based coalitions, and other actors working on the ground to combat substance misuse; and Coordinating the activities and related funding of sixteen Federal government agencies and departments to reduce the availability of and the demand for illicit substances. While ONDCP works broadly on substance misuse, it is focused on the country’s ongoing Opioid Crisis which is caused by the misuse of prescription drugs, heroin, and synthetic opioids like fentanyl. Director of ONDCP Jim Carroll Director of National Drug Control Policy The Honorable James W. “Jim” Carroll is the Director of National Drug Control Policy in the Executive Office of the President. He was unanimously confirmed by the United States Senate on January 2, 2019, and sworn in on January 31, 2019. Mr. Carroll previously served as the Acting Director and Deputy Director from February 2018 […] Learn more Statements & Releases New Tool Empowers Local Leaders to Take Action Against Rural Drug Addiction Healthcare Jan 31, 2020 Statements & Releases Statements on Decline in Drug Overdose Deaths Healthcare Jan 30, 2020 Statements & Releases ONDCP Announces 42 New Drug-Free Communities Grants Aimed at Preventing Youth Substance Use Dec 27, 2019 Statements & Releases Prize Winners Announced in $1.55M Challenge for New Solutions to Detect Opioids in International Mail Dec 12, 2019 Statements & Releases ONDCP, State Department Joint Statement on Fourth Annual North American Drug Dialogue Dec 9, 2019 Statements & Releases ONDCP Announces More Than $4 Million in Grants for Local Programs Combating the Opioid Crisis Nov 20, 2019 Statements & Releases ONDCP Releases Data on Coca Cultivation and Production Potential in Bolivia Nov 8, 2019 Statements & Releases ONDCP Statement on Chinese Prosecution and Sentencing of Fentanyl Traffickers and Producers Nov 7, 2019 Statements & Releases ONDCP Announces 150 New Drug-Free Communities Grants Aimed at Preventing Youth Substance Use Oct 30, 2019 FindTreatment.gov Launches to Help More Americans Find Treatment for Substance Use Disorders Oct 30, 2019 Previous 1 2 3 4 … 8 Next The White House Live Jobs Get Involved Copyright Policy Privacy Policy Twitter Facebook Instagram Contact News Remarks Briefings & Statements Presidential Actions Articles All News Issues Education National Security & Defense Budget & Spending Immigration Healthcare All Issue